    <div class="annotation-panel" style="padding-top:8px;">
      <div class="annotation">
        <div class="ann-tag">Design Decision 8</div>
        <div class="ann-text">The persistent "Waiting for 1 more payment after yours" banner closes the feedback loop participants said was missing in the first evaluation — they wanted to know when the whole transaction would be complete, not just their own portion.</div>
        <span class="ann-req">R2 — Real-time feedback</span>
      </div>
      <div class="annotation">
        <div class="ann-tag">Design Decision 9</div>
        <div class="ann-text">The group status panel shows all three participants and their payment states simultaneously. This satisfies the social transparency need: no one is left wondering whether their friend has paid or is still fumbling. This directly reduces social friction identified in the root user need.</div>
        <span class="ann-req">R3 — Multi-party coordination</span>
      </div>
      <div class="annotation">
        <div class="ann-tag">Design Decision 10</div>
        <div class="ann-text">The "Group balance remaining" block shows both the user's share ($80) and the live group total ($130) — giving context without requiring arithmetic. This is an application of Norman's principle that the system should do the computation, not the user.</div>
        <span class="ann-req">R6 — Low cognitive load</span>
      </div>
      <div class="annotation">
        <div class="ann-tag">Design Decision 11</div>
        <div class="ann-text">Apple Pay is pre-selected as the default method, minimizing the number of actions needed to complete the task. This reflects the Principle of Least Effort: the most likely action (contactless mobile payment) should require the fewest steps.</div>
        <span class="ann-req">R6 — Low cognitive load</span>
      </div>
    </div>
